SIMPLE: surd
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surd
<hw>Surd</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>surdus</ets>
deaf (whence the meaning, deaf to reason, irrational), perhaps akin to
E. <ets>swart</ets>. Cf. <er>Sordine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Net
having the sense of hearing; deaf.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<xex>surd</xex> . . . generation.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unheard.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Kenrick.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Involving surds; not capable of
being expressed in rational numbers; radical; irrational; <as>as, a
<ex>surd</ex> expression or quantity; a <ex>surd</ex>
number</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <def>Uttered, as an element of
speech, without tone, or proper vocal sound; voiceless; unintonated;
nonvocal; atonic; whispered; aspirated; sharp; hard, as <xex>f</xex>,
<xex>p</xex>, <xex>s</xex>, etc.; -- opposed to <xex>sonant</xex>. See
<xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>, ⟦sect⟧⟦sect⟧169, 179, 180.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surd</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Surd
<hw>Surd</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
quantity which can not be expressed by rational numbers; <as>thus,
⟦root⟧2 is a <ex>surd</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>A surd element of speech. See
<er>Surd</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surdal</ent>⟦br⟧
